  <Hero
    title="Stage 2: Reactive"
    subtitle="Watch for a trigger. Track which path it takes."
    date="Lenora AI workflows · march 2026"
    codeComment="// Horus Daisy Chain — Stage 2"
  />

  <div class="container">
    <div class="card article">
      <h2>Origin</h2>
      <p>See <a href="/daisy-chains/horus-daisy-chain-stage-1-passive/#origin">stage 1 — passive</a> for the full hardware-to-DDD mapping. Stage 2 corresponds to <strong>point 7: test vectors applied to scan chains</strong> — a known input (the trigger) with expected output patterns (the outcomes). If the observed output doesn't match any declared outcome, there's a fault.</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>What is stage 2</h2>
      <p>Stage 1 watches linear chains. Stage 2 watches for a <strong>trigger signal</strong>, then tracks which <strong>outcome path</strong> the chain follows. After the trigger, the flow can fork into multiple valid outcomes — executed, rejected, known errors. DCME classifies what happened.</p>
      <p>This is the equivalent of hardware boundary scan with expected output vectors — you know what went in, now verify which output pattern you got.</p>
      <p><strong>Requires stage 1.</strong> Reactive specs reuse the same adapters, matching engine, scan cell payloads, and correlation logic from stage 1.</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>Spec structure</h2>
      <pre>specs:
  &lt;name&gt;:
    mode: reactive
    trigger:
      via: &lt;adapter&gt;
      match: &#123; ... &#125;
    timeout: &lt;duration&gt;
    outcomes:
      &lt;outcome_name&gt;:
        - service: ...
          signal: ...
        - service: ...
          signal: ...
      &lt;outcome_name&gt;:
        - ...
      known_errors:
        &lt;error_name&gt;:
          - ...
    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <ul>
        <li><strong><code>trigger</code></strong> — the signal that starts chain tracking. DCME subscribes/watches for this. When seen, a new chain instance is created with the extracted <code>correlationId</code>.</li>
        <li><strong><code>outcomes</code></strong> — named paths the chain can follow after the trigger. Each outcome is an ordered list of links (same signal + matcher format as stage 1). DCME matches incoming signals against all outcomes simultaneously.</li>
        <li><strong><code>known_errors</code></strong> — expected failure paths. Still a valid outcome, but classified as an error. DCME reports which error, not just "it broke."</li>
        <li><strong><code>unknown_path</code></strong> — what to do if no outcome matches within timeout. This is the real bug detector: something happened that nobody defined.</li>
      </ul>

      <hr>

      <h2>Gate direction</h2>
      <p>Stage 2 adds the <strong><code>gate</code></strong> signal direction to emit and expect from stage 1:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong><code>gate</code></strong> — the chain pauses here until a condition is met. Not just "did it arrive" but "was a decision made." Used for scripts and approval workflows. Has its own <code>gate_timeout</code> separate from chain timeout.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Gates can resolve as approved, rejected, or timeout:</p>

      <pre>      - service: bluepill
        signal:
          direction: gate
          via: script
          match:
            script: compliance-check.sh
          gate_timeout: 10s
          on_approved:
            exit_code: 0
            continue: true
          on_rejected:
            exit_code: 1
            fallback_chain: rfq_manual_review
          on_timeout:
            fallback_chain: rfq_escalation</pre>

      <hr>

      <h2>Alert types</h2>
      <p>Inherits all alerts from stage 1 (chain break, latency threshold, sequence violation, orphan event), plus:</p>

      <h3>Unknown path</h3>
      <p>Trigger seen, but the chain followed none of the defined outcomes. Something happened that nobody declared. High-priority alert.</p>

      <h3>Gate hold</h3>
      <p>Chain paused at a decision point. Waiting for script completion or approval workflow.</p>

      <h3>Known error classified</h3>
      <p>Chain followed a <code>known_errors</code> path. Not a surprise — but tracked, counted, and surfaced in the UI.</p>

      <hr>

      <h2>Example: reactive chain definition</h2>
      <p>One example showing the format. Shows trigger, multiple outcomes, known_errors, gate direction, and unknown_path alert.</p>

      <pre>specs:
  example_lifecycle:
    mode: reactive
    trigger:
      via: nats
      match:
        subject: "requests.created.*"
    timeout: 10s

    outcomes:
      completed:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "results.completed.*"
        - service: notifier
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "notifications.sent.*"

      completed_with_review:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "results.completed.*"
        - service: reviewer
          signal:
            direction: gate
            via: script
            match:
              script: review-check.sh
              exit_code: 0
            gate_timeout: 10s
        - service: notifier
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "notifications.sent.*"

      rejected:
        - service: processor
          signal:
            direction: emit
            via: nats
            match:
              subject: "requests.rejected.*"

      known_errors:
        unavailable:
          - service: processor
            signal:
              direction: emit
              via: nats
              match:
                subject: "requests.error.*"
                body.code: SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE

    unknown_path: alert</pre>

      <hr>

      <h2>Outcome matching algorithm</h2>
      <p>The matching engine tracks all outcomes simultaneously per chain instance. See the <a href="/daisy-chains/daisy-chain-matcher-engine-spec/">daisy chain matcher engine spec</a> for the full implementation (<code>ChainInstance</code>, <code>ProcessSignal</code>, cursor tracking, timeout sweeps, and alert classification).</p>

      <p>Summary of the algorithm:</p>

      <ol>
        <li>Extract <code>correlationId</code> from body.</li>
        <li>Find the active chain instance for that correlation.</li>
        <li>For each outcome, check if the signal matches the <strong>next expected link</strong>.</li>
        <li>If it matches, advance that outcome's cursor.</li>
        <li>First outcome to complete all its links wins — chain is classified.</li>
        <li>If timeout expires and no outcome completed, check partial matches:
          <ul>
            <li>If one outcome is partially matched (some links fired), report as <strong>chain break</strong> with the outcome name and the link where it stopped.</li>
            <li>If no outcome has any matches, report as <strong>unknown path</strong>.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <hr>

      <h2>Relationship to stage 1</h2>
      <p>Stage 1 passive specs and stage 2 reactive specs can run simultaneously on the same traffic. A passive <code>order_fill</code> spec watches every fill chain link-by-link. A reactive <code>order_lifecycle</code> spec watches for order placement and classifies the outcome. They observe the same NATS subjects but answer different questions:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stage 1 asks:</strong> "Did every link in this chain fire in order?"</li>
        <li><strong>Stage 2 asks:</strong> "Given this trigger, which outcome did the system produce?"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
